{"id": "node:source/show/show-draft-v1.md", "path": "source/show/show-draft-v1.md", "file_name": "show-draft-v1.md", "node_type": "source_show_script", "title": "You Can Write a Book — Show Draft v1", "status": "draft", "tags": ["show", "source", "source_show_script", "you-can-write-a-book", "edinburgh-fringe"], "themes": ["permission_to_start", "shitty_first_draft", "writing_as_magic", "writing_as_hypnosis", "peer_feedback", "marks_on_the_page", "overcoming_the_blank_page", "creativity"], "metaphors": ["writing_as_magic", "writing_as_hypnosis", "fooling_yourself", "fooling_the_reader"], "topics": ["writing", "creativity", "live_performance", "audience_participation", "edinburgh_fringe"], "channel": "live_performance", "date_published": null, "risk": null, "cta": null, "trigger_type": null, "source_docs": [], "summary": "Shitty first draft of the Edinburgh Fringe show 'You Can Write a Book'. Opens with the audience immediately writing in their (branded) notebooks. Core argument: writing is a form of magic/hypnosis — you fool yourself into thinking it's worth writing, and sometimes the magic actually works. Audience shares what they wrote and gives feedback. Ends: 'Congratulations — you're now a writer.' Key gaps: no mention of Delivering the Impossible, no explicit book CTA, branded notebook/pen not scripted, section placeholders unexpanded (shitty first drafts, one inch window), no opening context or closing."}
{"id": "node:source/show/bird-by-bird-highlights.md", "path": "source/show/bird-by-bird-highlights.md", "file_name": "bird-by-bird-highlights.md", "node_type": "source_show_background", "title": "Bird by Bird — Anne Lamott (Kindle Highlights)", "status": "imported", "tags": ["bird-by-bird", "anne-lamott", "show", "source", "source_show_background", "you-can-write-a-book", "background-reading"], "themes": ["permission_to_start", "shitty_first_draft", "writing_as_hypnosis", "writing_as_magic", "showing_up_daily", "overcoming_the_blank_page", "publication_fantasy", "finding_your_voice", "peer_feedback", "writing_as_attention", "writing_as_observation", "writing_as_need", "managing_expectations"], "metaphors": ["scales_on_the_piano", "polaroid_developing", "trees_in_winter", "zorba_at_the_keyboard", "hypnotising_yourself", "vivid_and_continuous_dream"], "topics": ["writing", "creativity", "craft", "process", "publication", "voice", "attention", "structure"], "channel": null, "date_published": null, "risk": null, "cta": null, "trigger_type": null, "source_docs": [], "summary": "Kindle highlights from Bird by Bird by Anne Lamott. Key ideas: writing as daily practice (scales on the piano), writing as hypnotising yourself into believing in yourself, shitty first drafts, the publication fantasy vs reality, finding your own voice, sharing drafts with readers, and writing as attention and observation. Directly informs the show's themes of permission to start and writing as magic."}
{"id": "node:source/show/richard-toye-notes.md", "path": "source/show/richard-toye-notes.md", "file_name": "richard-toye-notes.md", "node_type": "source_show_background", "title": "Richard Toye — Notes", "status": "draft", "tags": ["richard-toye", "show", "source", "source_show_background", "you-can-write-a-book", "non-fiction-writing", "structure"], "themes": ["non_fiction_structure", "writing_authority", "why_you_why_us_why_now_why_this", "audience_address", "framing_a_book"], "metaphors": [], "topics": ["writing", "non-fiction", "structure", "introduction", "authority"], "channel": null, "date_published": null, "risk": null, "cta": null, "trigger_type": null, "source_docs": [], "summary": "Two-session course by Professor Richard Toye (Exeter, 19 books, Literary Director Royal Historical Society) on writing nonfiction book proposals. Session 1: why write a proposal (sharpen message, present idea, give publisher permission); four types of nonfiction (information, advocacy, how-to, experience); Aristotle's ethos/pathos/logos; the 2 biggest mistakes (unclear argument; excess modesty/gap-filling language); core message homework: Why This / Why Me / Why Now. Session 2: proposal basics (10-30 pages); substance (title, description with Why This/Me/Now, chapter synopsis); language and tone; Why This (6 reasons), Why Now (5 reasons), Why Me (7 credentials); market identification; competition framing; dealing with editorial comments; contract negotiation; routes to trade publication. Note: the show uses Why You/Why Us/Why Now/Why This — a 4-question adaptation that splits Why Me into performer credibility and audience stake."}
{"id": "node:source/show/prisms-not-mirrors.md", "path": "source/show/prisms-not-mirrors.md", "file_name": "prisms-not-mirrors.md", "node_type": "source_show_background", "title": "Prisms, not mirrors", "status": "active", "tags": ["borges", "prisms", "show", "source", "source_show_background", "you-can-write-a-book", "philosophy-of-writing"], "themes": ["prisms_not_mirrors", "writing_as_transformation", "no_passive_aesthetic", "point_of_view", "writing_as_distortion", "writing_as_magic"], "metaphors": ["prism", "mirror", "distortion", "transformation"], "topics": ["writing", "philosophy", "point_of_view", "creativity", "perception"], "channel": null, "date_published": null, "risk": null, "cta": null, "trigger_type": null, "source_docs": [], "summary": "Mark's disagreement with Borges: there are only prisms, no mirrors. You can't stop distorting what you see. Applied to the show: the opening writing exercise looks like neutral recording but is already transformation — proving the claim by doing it. Bridges to Delivering the Impossible via 'point of view is worth 80 IQ points'. Strong candidate for the show's philosophical centrepiece and the answer to 'Why this?'"}
{"id": "node:source/show/tenth-of-an-arse.md", "path": "source/show/tenth-of-an-arse.md", "file_name": "tenth-of-an-arse.md", "node_type": "source_show_background", "title": "The Tenth of an Arse", "status": "active", "tags": ["show", "source", "source_show_background", "you-can-write-a-book", "shitty-first-draft", "iteration"], "themes": ["shitty_first_draft", "peer_feedback", "iteration", "writing_as_discovery", "the_gap_between_intention_and_reception", "permission_to_start"], "metaphors": ["tenth_of_an_arse", "half_arsed"], "topics": ["writing", "feedback", "iteration", "craft", "revision"], "channel": null, "date_published": null, "risk": null, "cta": null, "trigger_type": null, "source_docs": [], "summary": "Mark's coinage: the first draft is not just a shitty first draft (Lamott) but a tenth of an arse. Discovered while writing Delivering the Impossible — wrote something, thought he'd nailed it, showed it to readers, discovered how incomplete it was. Extends Lamott's permission-to-start with honest measurement of the gap. Directly grounds the sharing exercise in the show. Stage-ready phrase: funny, specific, earned from lived experience."}
{"id": "node:source/show/show-draft-v1-gaps.md", "path": "source/show/show-draft-v1-gaps.md", "file_name": "show-draft-v1-gaps.md", "node_type": "source_show_notes", "title": "Show Draft v1 — Gaps and Notes", "status": "active", "tags": ["show", "source", "source_show_notes", "you-can-write-a-book", "gaps"], "themes": ["show_development", "script_gaps", "provenance"], "metaphors": [], "topics": ["writing", "show_development", "editorial_notes"], "channel": null, "date_published": null, "risk": null, "cta": null, "trigger_type": null, "source_docs": [], "summary": "Running gaps and notes file for show-draft-v1.md. Tracks what works, what is missing, resolved issues, and open questions. Updated as the script develops."}
